ABSTCT: ree new (1-3) and six known rotenoids (5-10), along with three known isoavones (11-13), were isolated
from the leave Milleia oblata ssp. teitensis. A new glycosylated isoavone (4), four known isoavones (14-18) and one
known chalcone (19) were isolated from the root wood extract of the same plant. e structures were elucidated by NMR
spectroscopic and mass spectrometric analyses. e absolute conguration of the chiral compounds was established by
comparison of experimental ECD and VCD data with those calculated for the possible stereoisomers. is the rst report on
the use of VCD to assign the absolute conguration of rotenoids. e crude leaves and root wood extracts displayed anti-RSV
(human respiratory syncytial virus) activity with IC
50
values 0.7 g/mL and 3.4 g/mL, respectively. Compounds 6, 8, 10, 11,
and 14 showed anti-RSV activity with IC
50
values 0.4 - 10 M, while compound 3 exhibited anti-HRV-2 (human rhinovirus 2)
activity with IC
50
of 4.2 M. Most of the compounds showed low cytotoxicity for laryngeal carcinoma (HEp-2) cells, however
compounds 3, 11, and 14 exhibited low cytotoxicity also in primary lung broblasts. is is the rst report on rotenoids
showing antiviral activity against RSV and HRV viruses.

e n to * transition at 348-360 nm is generally weak and
for many rotenoids it has not been observed, and thus may

absolute conguration.

probe. e spectra were processed using the MestReNova
14.1 soware and were referenced to the residual solvent
peak. LC-ESIMS data were acquired on a Waters Micromass

O/MeCN
(5:95 to 95:5, with 1% HCO

HRESIMS spectra were acquired with a Q-TOF LC/MS

Cells and viruses. Human laryngeal epidermoid carci
noma (HEp-2) cells were cultivated in Dulbeccos Modied
Eagles Medium (DMEM) supplemented with 8% fetal calf
serum and 292 g/mL of L-glutamine. Human adenocar
cinoma cells of uterine cervix (HeLa) cells were grown
in Eagles minimum essential medium supplemented with
5% fetal calf serum and antibiotics. Human embryonic
Chem & Bio Engineering
pubs.acs.org/ChemBioEng
Article
10
lung broblasts (HELF) were grown in Eagles minimum
essential medium supplemented with 5% fetal calf serum,
L-glutamine and antibiotics. e A2 strain of human
respiratory syncytial virus (RSV) (ATCC VR-1540) was
used. e RSV stock was prepared and stored as described
previously by Lundin, et al.
50
In some experiments, strain
HGP of human rhinovirus 2 (HRV-2) (ATCC, VR-482)
was used.
Antiviral assays. e RSV plaque reduction assay was
performed as described previously
,
with some modications.
Briey, the test extracts and compounds were serially
diluted at a range of 1.6-200 g/mL and 0.16-100 M
respectively in DMEM supplemented with 2% heat-inacti
vated fetal calf serum, 60 g/mL of penicillin, 100 g/mL
of streptomycin, and 292 g/mL of L-glutamine (DMEM-
M), and then added to one-day-old cultures of HEp-2 cell
in 24-well cluster plates. Following 15 min of incubation
at 37 in a humidied atmosphere comprising 5% CO
2
(incubator), the cells were inoculated with 50100 plaque-
forming units (PFU) of RSV A2. Aer incubation of the
virus-compound mixture with cells for 2.5 h in the CO
2
incubator, the inoculum was removed and 750 l of 1%
methylcellulose solution in DMEM-M comprising the same
concentration of test compound/extract was added and le
for a further three days in the CO
2
incubator. e cells
were stained with a 1% solution of crystal violet, and the
viral plaques were counted under a microscope. Ribavirin,
a drug approved for the treatment of RSV disease, was
used as a positive control whereas DMSO at concentrations
corresponding to these present in the test compounds was
used as solvent control.
e anti-HRV-2 activity of extracts and compounds was
assessed by a tetrazolium-based colorimetric assay
52
with
some modications. Briey, serial ve-fold dilutions of test
samples (0.16 -100 M) in EMEM supplemented with 2%
fetal calf serum, 1% pest stock, 1% L-glutamine stock, 30
mM MgCl
2
, and 20 mM HEPES (pH 7.1) (EMEM-M)
were added to one-day-old cultures of HeLa cells seeded
in 96 well cluster plates. Following the incubation of cells
with test samples for 3 h at 34C CO
2
incubator, 100
tissue culture infectious doses (TCID
50
) in EMEM-M were
added. In some wells addition of the test samples and
the virus was omied to serve as the virus control and
uninfected cell control respectively. Aer incubation of the
test plates in the CO
2
incubator for 3 days, the CellTiter
96 Aqueous one solution reagent (Promega, Madison, WI,
USA) was added, and following further incubation of plates
in the CO
2
incubator for 1 h, the absorbance was recorded
at 490 nm. e % of the test sample protection of cells
against HRV-2 infection was calculated as (Absorbance of
the test sample-virus control) 100 / Absorbance of the cell
control-virus control.
e cell toxicity assay. e tetrazolium-based cytotoxicity
assay using a CellTiter 96 Aqueous one solution reagent
(Promega, Madison, WI, USA) was performed for the test
extracts and isolated compounds in HEp-2, HELF, and
HeLa cells as described previously.
50
Optical spectroscopy. UV absorbance and ECD spectra
were collected simultaneously on a 0.02 mg/mL sample
in MeOH using a path length of 10 mm on a ChiraS
can-plus (Applied Photophysics) with a scan speed of 30
nm/min under a continuous N
2
-ow. e solvent spectra
were recorded under identical conditions to remove solvent
bands in the UV spectra, and to baseline correct the ECD
spectra. IR and VCD spectra were recorded simultaneously
on a ChiralIR-2X (Biotools) equipped with a dual PEM
system running at resolution of 4 cm
-1
and the central
PEM frequency set to 1400 cm
-1
. Samples were dissolved in
CDCl
3
, and a cell equipped with BaF
2
windows and a path
length of 100 m and a total of 96000 scans were recorded
(32 h). e nal experimental VCD spectra were obtained
by subtracting the solvent VCD spectrum recorded under
identical conditions.
Calculations. A low energy conformation library of
postulated compounds 1 and 2 in both the cis and
trans conguration were created using PCModel
53
with the
incorporated MMFF94 force eld. All conformers within
a cut-o of 5 kcal/mol from the lowest energy conformer
were retained and subjected to DFT optimization and
spectral calculations at the B3LYP/6-311++G(d,p) level of
theory. DFT calculations were performed on conformers
exhibiting a Boltzmann weight higher than 1% (based on
Enthalpy). e solvent was implicitly taken into account
using the IEFPCM model as implemented in the Gaussian
suite. All DFT level calculations were performed using
the Gaussian 16 soware package
54
with tight convergence
criteria and ultrane integration grids. For each conformer
IR absorbance and VCD spectra were created by applying a
Lorentzian broadening with full half width at half maximum
of 10 cm
-1
and subsequent Boltzmann weighted based on
their enthalpies. To compare the calculated spectra with the
experimental one, a spectrascaling factor of 0.98 was applied
on the calculated frequencies.
